        <p><strong>Introduction</strong></p>
        <p>
            Many Open University students wonder what classification they will be awarded for their degree qualification. This tool aims to provide an estimate of the class you are 
            likely to receive using the points and grades you have achieved for each module, or those you predict you’ll be awarded. Whilst the university provides the official guidance 
            document <em><a href="https://help.open.ac.uk/documents/policies/working-out-your-class-of-honours/files/50/honours-class-working-out.pdf">Working Out Your Class of Honours</a></em>, 
            some find this a little hard to follow. To help with this, various unofficial tools have been created, such as the widely known and reliable 
            <a href="http://cleveret.net/?page_id=29">Cleveret calculator</a> (<em>Thank you to them for inspiring this version!</em>). 
            This tool hopes to add another option, with some hopefully useful features such as saving your module list for later.
        </p>

        <p><strong>Disclaimer and notes on limitations of the tool</strong></p>
        <p>
            Please be aware that the tool is <strong>completely unofficial</strong>, provides an estimate only, and has various necessary limitations. 
            The tool cannot for example take into account your individual circumstances or the regulations of your degree subject, and it will not check for any compulsary modules 
            or excluded combinations. Efforts have been made to ensure its accuracy, but responsibility can’t be taken for wrong results, especially for less standard circumstances 
            such as transferred credit. <strong>Always</strong> consult the official document from the Open University, or contact Student Support to discuss your individual 
            qualification if you're in any doubt.
        </p>

        <p>
            Should you have any queries or find an error, please feel free to <a href="mailto:lucy.parry@gmail.com">contact me</a>, or if you're that way inclined, 
            issues or pull requests are very welcome on the <a href="">GitHub repository</a>.
        </p>

        <p><strong>How do undergraduate honours degrees work?</strong></p>
        <p>
            The OU uses the same classification system as other UK universities, in which degrees awarded 'with honours' are given one of four classifications; first, upper 
            second (2:1), lower second (2:2) and third. Degrees can also be awarded without honours, these are usually referred to as 'ordinary degrees' and do not receive a 
            classification.
        </p>

        <p><strong>How is the degree class calculated for OU honours degrees?</strong></p>
        <p>
            An OU honours degree consists of 360 module credits in total, with at least 240 credits at level 2 or above, and at least 120 credits at level 3. Level 1 module 
            grades do not count towards the classification, so up to 240 credits at level 2 or above are used to calculate the overall class (the counting credit can be less 
            if transferred credit has been used).
        </p>
        <p>
            The best 120 module credits at level 3 are taken first, and are given a score based on the amount of credit (e.g. 60, 30), multiplied by the grade (where Distinction 
            is 1 through to Pass 4 as 4). Each of these scores is then multiplied by 2 to give it double weighting in the calculation. Any remaining credit to be used is then given 
            a score using the same process, without the double weighting. In practice, for most degrees without credit transfer, this is generally the level 2 modules.</p>
        <p>
            Each of the calculated module scores are then summed to give an overall initial score for the degree. Where 240 credits have been used, this will be between 360 and 1440, 
            and the classification is given as follows:
        </p>
        <p>
            <table class="table table-sm table-hover table-bordered table-responsive-sm5">
                <tbody>
                    <tr>
                        <td style="width: 50%;">First</td>
                        <td style="width: 50%;">630 or less</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td style="width: 50%;">Upper Second (2:1)</td>
                        <td style="width: 50%;">631 to 900</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td style="width: 50%;">Lower Second (2:2)</td>
                        <td style="width: 50%;">901 to 1170</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td style="width: 50%;">Third</td>
                        <td style="width: 50%;">1171 to 1440</td>
                    </tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </p>
        <p>
            A 'quality assurance' test is then performed to check that the best 60 credits at level 3 meets or exceeds the initial classification. If both the points total and 
            quality assurance are satisfied, you will be awarded that classification.
        </p>
