        <p><strong>Notes about transferred credit and compulsary modules</strong></p>
        <p>
            Where transferred credit is used, less than 240 credits of grades are counted and the thresholds for each degree class are adjusted on a pro rata basis. The tool will attempt to
            take this into account if you add a module with the amount of transferred credit you have been given and the grade set to 'transferred'. The tool will also allow you to mark a
            module as 'compulsary' so it will always be counted in the calculation. Note that both cases are notoriously tricky, so always contact the OU to discuss if in any doubt, and never trust the estimates of tools like this alone!
        </p>

        <p><strong>How does this work? Are you storing my data somewhere?</strong> </p>
        <p>
            The calculation is done entirely in your own web browser and no data on your modules or qualification is stored or sent back to a server. 
            The link feature works by simply encoding the list of module details into the URL, which is read back again when you request the page. 
            For fellow programmers, the code is available on the <a href="https://github.com/LucyParry/degree-class-estimator/tree/master/src">GitHub repo</a>.  
            It uses client-side <a href="https://dotnet.microsoft.com/apps/aspnet/web-apps/blazor">Blazor</a>, an interesting new web framework from Microsoft 
            which allows C# code to run on the client using WebAssembly (I prefer writing C# to JavaScript any day of the week, so I think this is great!)
        </p>

